## Modulation  

A signal at baseband is often used to [modulate](/Modulation) a higher frequency [carrier signal](/Carrier_signal) in order that it may be transmitted via radio. Modulation results in shifting the signal up to much higher frequencies (radio frequencies, or RF) than it originally spanned. A key consequence of the usual [double‑sideband](/Double_sideband) [amplitude modulation](/Amplitude_modulation) (AM) is that the range of frequencies the signal spans (its spectral [bandwidth](/Bandwidth_(signal_processing))) is doubled. Thus, the RF bandwidth of a signal (measured from the lowest frequency as opposed to 0 Hz) is twice its baseband bandwidth. Steps may be taken to reduce this effect, such as [single‑sideband modulation](/Single‑sideband_modulation). Conversely, some transmission schemes such as [frequency modulation](/Frequency_modulation) use even more bandwidth.  

